Y by nosaj, Williamgolly, Adventure10, Mango247SolutionNote that \begin{align*}(k^2+1)k!&=k(k\cdot k!)+k!=k\left[(k+1)!-k!\right]+k!\\&=k(k+1)!-k\cdot k!+k!=k(k+1)!-k!(k-1).\end{align*}

Hence for all positive integer $k$ we have \begin{align*}b_k&=a_1+a_2+a_3+\cdots + a_k\\&=\cancel{1\cdot 2!}-1!\cdot 0+\cancel{2\cdot 3!}-\cancel{2!\cdot 1}+\cancel{3\cdot 4!}-\cancel{3!\cdot 2} + \cdots + k(k+1)!-\cancel{k!(k-1)}\\&=k(k+1)!\end{align*}

Thus \[\dfrac{a_{k}}{b_{k}}=\dfrac{(k^2+1)k!}{k(k+1)!}=\dfrac{k^2+1}{k(k+1)}=\dfrac{k^2+1}{k^2+k}\] and for sufficiently large even integers $k$ we have $b_k-a_k=k^2+k-(k^2+1)=k-1$.  Substituting $k=100$ gives $b_{100}-a_{100}=\boxed{99}$.

