Let $\frac mn = e$. Substitute $y=4x^2$ into $x = y^2 + e$ to obtain $x = 16x^4 + e$. We want quartic $16x^4 -x + e$ to have only one repeated real root, and thus we want it to have discriminant 0. Hopefully you remember the quartic discriminant, which for a polynomial $ax^4 + bx^3 + cx^2 + dx + e$ is



\begin{align*}
\Delta = & \, 256a^{3}e^{3}-192a^{2}bde^{2}-128a^{2}c^{2}e^{2}+144a^{2}cd^{2}e\\[4pt]&{}-27a^{2}d^{4}+144ab^{2}ce^{2}-6ab^{2}d^{2}e-80abc^{2}de\\[4pt]&{}+18abcd^{3}+16ac^{4}e-4ac^{3}d^{2}-27b^{4}e^{2}+18b^{3}cde\\[4pt]&{}-4b^{3}d^{3}-4b^{2}c^{3}e+b^{2}c^{2}d^{2}\,.
\end{align*}

Luckily, our quartic has $b = c = d = 0$, so we focus on the terms that only involve $a$, $d$, and $e$. Thus we end up with $256a^3 e^3 - 27a^2d^4 = 0$, and plugging in $a=16$ and $d = -1$ we get $256\left(16^3\right)e^3 - 27\left(16^2\right) = 0$ which yields $e = \frac{3}{16}$. Thus, $m=3$, $n=16$, and $m + n = \boxed{19.}$



Don't remember the discriminant of a quartic? No problem! You can always derive it as the resultant of a polynomial and its derivative. For instance see pages 5 and 6 of Henry Woody's handout on polynomial resultants. Of course finding the derivative of the polynomial is, well, calculus (hence the "No Calculus" in quotes). But hey at least finding the derivative of a univariate polynomial will only ever involve simple applications of the power rule, so you could still call the derivation "Minimal Calculus" if you wanted.

